we're answering questions.

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:23.320
We're going to get some more questions, right?

00:02:23.320 --> 00:02:25.360
There's nothing unique about that, but there are some

00:02:25.360 --> 00:02:26.839
improvements that we can, we can do.

00:02:26.839 --> 00:02:31.839
So for example, you know, your team or you create this document, uh, you've

00:02:31.839 --> 00:02:36.960
done all this analysis, you email or file share this thing, your collaborators

00:02:36.960 --> 00:02:40.880
will then review it and provide some feedback, they say, ah, it's garbage.

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:42.960
Do it on this dataset or, oh, I love it.

00:02:42.960 --> 00:02:44.639
Just change this color or whatever it is.

00:02:44.960 --> 00:02:48.279
Um, and they come back with questions and we go around on this cycle.

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:48.679
Right.

00:02:48.679 --> 00:02:51.520
And so everybody that raised their hand is probably very familiar with this.

00:02:52.759 --> 00:02:55.839
But especially if you were to approach it with this lowest

00:02:55.839 --> 00:02:57.479
common denominator of emailing.

00:02:57.839 --> 00:02:59.960
There's a lot of things that you kind of lose, right?

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.199
You have to make sure are the right people viewing your document.

00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:05.880
Are they even viewing the right version of your document?

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:10.759
Um, you are, it's over time when projects kind of grow, people will add

00:03:10.759 --> 00:03:12.639
onto the project or leave a project.

00:03:12.919 --> 00:03:15.639
And anything you've emailed now is kind of like lost, right?

00:03:15.639 --> 00:03:20.160
It becomes a work for that under other team or for your team to have to kind of

00:03:20.160 --> 00:03:22.240
make sure all of this is managed appropriately.

00:03:22.520 --> 00:03:27.600
And so all that time that you spent over here, kind of collecting the data and

