client subscribes to a particular dataset, their documentation represents

00:13:34.640 --> 00:13:38.880
now their data, and this is now all of the data that we have available to us.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:42.280
And this is now all kind of through an automated pipeline.

00:13:42.559 --> 00:13:47.640
And so it has saved basically weeks of work and has greatly improved our, our

00:13:47.640 --> 00:13:51.559
ability to determine who's changed, what, when they changed it, et cetera,

00:13:51.559 --> 00:13:52.679
and give us a lot more providence.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:56.520
And this is all kind of built on top of this infrastructure and benefits the clients.

00:13:56.960 --> 00:13:59.359
The clients come back to us saying like, this is great.

00:13:59.359 --> 00:14:00.559
Now it's a single source.

00:14:00.760 --> 00:14:03.159
There's no worry about what version I'm looking at, right.

00:14:03.159 --> 00:14:05.880
As we were talking about earlier, that was part of our hypothesis.

00:14:06.400 --> 00:14:08.440
And so they can go to that resource.

00:14:08.440 --> 00:14:10.640
They can find it, their search functionality, all the things

00:14:10.640 --> 00:14:11.679
you'd expect out of the web.

00:14:11.799 --> 00:14:14.400
So that's been a really, really cool, cool win.

00:14:15.679 --> 00:14:18.919
The second showcase is a data browser.

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:24.200
And so one of the teams that works specifically on our genomics product

00:14:24.599 --> 00:14:28.599
wanted a way to kind of elevate some of the counts that they find in the

00:14:28.599 --> 00:14:33.039
dataset so that the clients and other people can basically be able to change

00:14:33.039 --> 00:14:35.640
some of the parameters and be able to pull out what they want.

00:14:35.640 --> 00:14:39.080
And the reason I like to highlight this one is because originally one of our

00:14:39.080 --> 00:14:42.280
hypotheses was if we build something like this, if we provide that

00:14:42.280 --> 00:14:45.960
infrastructure, we can reduce the time that subject matter experts

00:14:46.520 --> 00:14:48.640
can get towards an output, right?

00:14:48.679 --> 00:14:52.280
So now we have subject matter experts, thank you, subject matter experts

00:14:52.280 --> 00:14:56.559
that are working on this and can develop this stuff with technologies

00:14:56.559 --> 00:14:58.359
such as Quarto and build these.

00:14:58.679 --> 00:15:02.320
And so in a matter of like two weeks without having any experience like

00:15:02.359 --> 00:15:06.599
with Quarto or R Markdown or even JavaScript, they were able to build this

00:15:06.599 --> 00:15:09.479
and it's multilingual in the sense that parts of it are built with R,

00:15:09.479 --> 00:15:10.960
parts of it are built with Python.

00:15:11.320 --> 00:15:14.679
And I thought that's a really cool highlight to make.

00:15:14.679 --> 00:15:18.640
And so shout out to Prita Ghosh on our team who was able to build this out.

00:15:19.960 --> 00:15:25.520
The third one is a favorite of mine because Connect allows hosting of APIs.

00:15:26.239 --> 00:15:31.919
We can now provide an ability, a utility for individuals to be able to like

00:15:32.039 --> 00:15:32.960
create this stepping stone.

00:15:32.960 --> 00:15:35.960
So we create this infrastructure that allows other people to interact with the

00:15:35.960 --> 00:15:39.719
data in a programmatic way so that they can go ahead and build additional

00:15:40.919 --> 00:15:41.719
capabilities.

00:15:41.719 --> 00:15:48.080
And so in this case, it gives us a lot of flexibility, similar to how an R

00:15:48.159 --> 00:15:52.119
package or a Python library would kind of encapsulate functions.

00:15:52.320 --> 00:15:55.640
We can now just build this in the language agnostic manner for people

00:15:55.640 --> 00:15:57.000
to consume that information.

00:15:57.320 --> 00:16:01.679
And so this is a extremely helpful utility that is now enabled by that.

00:16:01.679 --> 00:16:05.640
And so shout out to Tyler Lifke and Conrad who helped build this.

00:16:06.960 --> 00:16:09.599
Now, the fourth one is kind of experimental.

00:16:09.719 --> 00:16:12.119
And I don't have a screenshot because it's still early.

00:16:12.599 --> 00:16:17.119
But Connect, being this kind of hosting platform, obviously supports a lot of

00:16:17.119 --> 00:16:18.479
the things that I had mentioned earlier.

00:16:18.960 --> 00:16:22.760
But what we wanted to do is we wanted to kind of push the boundaries and see

00:16:22.760 --> 00:16:24.479
what can Connect actually do.

00:16:24.679 --> 00:16:28.000
We have a desire of building web applications, right?

00:16:28.239 --> 00:16:30.719
But we didn't necessarily want to build it in Shiny.

00:16:30.719 --> 00:16:35.520
There are certain limitations that Shiny has that was preventing us from

00:16:35.520 --> 00:16:36.679
kind of being able to go forward.

00:16:37.039 --> 00:16:40.960
And we want to see, can you build a web app in a more traditional, let's say,

00:16:41.239 --> 00:16:44.719
like a React framework or something like that and be able to publish that to Connect?

00:16:44.760 --> 00:16:47.520
I've seen examples of this by other companies doing it.

00:16:48.159 --> 00:16:51.799
And so we don't have JavaScript developers in-house to be able to do that.

00:16:51.840 --> 00:16:57.119
And we came across this framework called Reflex, which is a pure Python

00:16:57.239 --> 00:17:01.280
framework, basically a wrapper for Next.js, which is a framework for React.

00:17:02.239 --> 00:17:06.839
And the team was able to actually go through and with a little bit of help

00:17:06.839 --> 00:17:10.880
from Posit Solutions Engineering, we were able to come up with an MVP and

00:17:10.880 --> 00:17:14.959
actually deploy this on Connect so that people could actually engage with that

00:17:15.359 --> 00:17:17.920
content, which I thought was amazing.

00:17:17.920 --> 00:17:20.520
So this really expands the possibilities of what's there.

00:17:20.520 --> 00:17:24.760
Now, is it a little bit like, you know, unstable in terms of like, hey, this

00:17:24.760 --> 00:17:28.119
isn't necessarily purely supported, perhaps, but I just wanted to kind of

00:17:28.119 --> 00:17:28.959
showcase some of that.

00:17:30.239 --> 00:17:33.000
So some of the feedback.

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:35.199
So drawbacks, it's a little bit hard.

00:17:35.199 --> 00:17:38.160
Configuration's a little bit hard to wrestle in the beginning.

00:17:38.439 --> 00:17:41.760
Management of content across all of these systems was a little bit tricky.

00:17:41.760 --> 00:17:43.839
It's solvable, but, you know, that's that.

00:17:44.239 --> 00:17:46.239
And then not all content types are supported.

00:17:46.760 --> 00:17:49.880
So it's not, you know, all puppies and rainbows, as I like to say, but, you

00:17:49.880 --> 00:17:53.520
know, we were able to kind of be able to get there and there's a lot of benefits.

00:17:53.520 --> 00:17:57.280
So deployment and server management, because we use the infrastructure as

00:17:57.280 --> 00:17:59.479
code and its possibility is fantastic.

00:17:59.880 --> 00:18:00.880
We're really excited.

00:18:01.640 --> 00:18:05.680
We've excited our internal team members because they can very quickly see outputs

00:18:05.680 --> 00:18:06.640
from what they're building.

00:18:07.239 --> 00:18:09.959
They get excited and it kind of elevates the company as a whole.

00:18:10.319 --> 00:18:13.680
We've improved the way obviously our clients have consumed information.

00:18:14.160 --> 00:18:17.160
We've improved the speed at which we can deliver and make these updates.

00:18:18.079 --> 00:18:21.520
We've given, we've gotten better business insights.

00:18:21.520 --> 00:18:24.520
We can not only, we can see some of the activity and who's, are they even

00:18:24.520 --> 00:18:26.000
looking at the documentation, right?

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.280
Something that if you were just to email, you wouldn't be able to see.

00:18:28.640 --> 00:18:33.599
And it's just opened up possibilities as I've kind of mentioned in the last slide.

00:18:33.839 --> 00:18:36.959
So a big thank you to the team at Concert AI.

00:18:36.959 --> 00:18:39.520
There's a lot of people, but these are kind of core people that

00:18:39.959 --> 00:18:41.359
have helped out on the project.

00:18:41.719 --> 00:18:44.160
Eli from Atorus has been a fantastic resource.

00:18:44.160 --> 00:18:48.239
And then obviously Posit for accepting my proposal to speak here.

00:18:48.839 --> 00:18:49.160
Thank you.

00:18:51.520 --> 00:18:52.040
Thank you.

